{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64e9abc1-4dae-4398-bd60-242e232097e0","content":"Here's what I found:\n\n**`my_app/views.py:3`** — `datetime.now()` called directly\n\n```python\nnow = datetime.now()\n```\n\nThis is hard to test because you can't control the clock in unit tests.\n\n### Recommended fix\n\nUse Django's `django.utils.timezone.now` and inject it or use `freezegun`/`time-machine` to mock it:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThen in tests you can freeze time:\n\n```python\nfrom freezegun import freeze_time\n\n@freeze_time(\"2026-01-01\")\ndef test_index(self):\n    ...\n```\n\n**Summary:** 1 untestable static found — a bare `datetime.now()` call in `views.py`. Switching to `timezone.now()` also fixes the common Django pitfall of naive vs. aware datetimes. Want me to apply the fix?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98e7c0de-409a-4238-85ce-373e5e97fe96","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"9829:2EAF75:130A2B6:17F0EF2:69FFF3B3"},"id":"93f00cf1-2b7f-4b98-8a3a-0d10b6d6dca8","timestamp":"2026-05-10T02:55:53.851Z","parentId":"61a52067-5338-412e-862d-b93bb329649a"}
